{
    "analysis": "From the previous step: global thresholds (P95/P05) were computed for all metric, trace, and log component-KPIs using the full available series. Then data were filtered to the incident window (2022-03-21 23:30 to 2022-03-22 00:00 UTC+8). Aggregated results show: many adservice metric KPIs exceeded their P95 (commonly 3 points in the 30-point window) across JVM/runtime/GC/memory metrics; trace anomalies (both above-P95 and below-P05) are present across shippingservice and recommendationservice variants; log.row_count deviations occurred in many services (frontend, productcatalogservice, cartservice, currencyservice, shippingservice, recommendationservice). At this stage we have many per-(component,KPI) anomaly counts, but we have not converted those counts into concrete faults (consecutive anomalous subsequences). The next step is to identify actual fault runs (consecutive anomalous points) in metric series so we can locate candidate root cause components and the precise occurrence times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the stored metric_thresholds and metric_window_df in the kernel, detect consecutive anomalous runs per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) where value > p95. For each run compute: cmdb_id, kpi_name, run_length (consecutive points count), start_ts (earliest timestamp in run), end_ts (latest timestamp in run), max_value_in_run, p95, breach_ratio = (max_value_in_run - p95) / p95. Keep only runs with run_length >= 2. Store full result in kernel variable metric_fault_runs. Return a compact table (max 20 rows) of the top runs sorted by breach_ratio descending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, run_length, start_ts, end_ts, max_value_in_run, breach_ratio. Also return a small summary table of number_of_runs per cmdb_id (top 10 components by number_of_runs). If metric_fault_runs is empty, return an explicit empty indicator."
}

{
    "analysis": "The last Executor step produced candidate_trace_anomalies for the shortlisted components. Key derivations: frontend2-0 exhibits the earliest and numerous trace anomalies beginning at 2022-03-21 23:30 (UTC+8) affecting calls to shippingservice2-0 and adservice2-0; several other services (cartservice-2, paymentservice-0/1, recommendationservice-0) show trace anomalies later (~23:35–23:41). Node-2 has strong metric-level network spikes but no trace anomalies in the window, suggesting host/network telemetry noise or a non-application-level issue. Also, metric_fault_runs identified very high breach ratios on some containers (emailservice-2, cartservice-2, paymentservice-0) but their earliest metric-run times are later than frontend2-0’s trace anomalies. At this point we cannot finalize the root cause because we need log-level corroboration for the early trace anomalies (especially frontend2-0 → shippingservice2-0 / adservice2-0) and to confirm whether the early trace anomalies correspond to a downstream faulty component.\n\nWhat should be done next: analyze logs for the top candidates (frontend2-0, shippingservice2-0, adservice2-0) plus the other metric-severe containers (emailservice-2, cartservice-2, paymentservice-0/1) and node-2 in the incident window to find earliest log deviations (log.row_count or log.error_count) and any error messages. This will help determine which faulty component is both anomalous in metrics and implicated by traces and logs (the most downstream faulty component in trace chains).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the kernel tables log_thresholds and log_window_df (incident window 2022-03-21 23:30 to 2022-03-22 00:00 UTC+8), produce a compact log-anomaly summary for these candidate components: frontend2-0, shippingservice2-0, adservice2-0, cartservice-2, paymentservice-0, paymentservice-1, emailservice-2, node-2. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) among those candidates compute: p95, p05 (from log_thresholds), count_total (points in window), count_above_p95, count_below_p05, earliest_above_ts, earliest_below_ts, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. Return a single aggregated table (one row per cmdb_id-log_name), limited to top 20 rows, sorted by the earliest non-null timestamp among earliest_above_ts and earliest_below_ts ascending (earliest anomalies first). Also search error_logs_df for any rows whose cmdb_id is in the candidate list and return up to 20 matching error log rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, message). If a candidate has no log or error-log entries, indicate NA for those fields. Store the aggregated log table in kernel variable candidate_log_anomalies and the error-log subset in kernel variable candidate_error_logs_subset."}

